<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-185-223 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 541 788</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 1 1991 v8 n13 p14(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM NetView, ATandamp;T Accumaster to wed with software bond. (utilityprograms enable multivendor network management systems tointeroperate)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Musich, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Contracts)American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    T; IBM.andO;Product:   NetView 3.0 (Computer network software) (Marketing)Accumaster Integrator 2.0 (Network management software)(Marketing).andO;Topic:     Cooperative AgreementNetwork Management SoftwareInteroperabilityLocal Area NetworksUtility Programs.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Paula MusichandM;NEW YORK -- Joining their network-management systems in an interfaithmarriage, IBM and ATandamp;T last week announced plans to allow IBM's NetView andATandamp;T's Accumaster Integrator to communicate.andM;At a press conference here, the two industry giants announced an agreement todevelop software links that will allow the minicomputer-based AccumasterIntegrator and mainframe-based NetView to share configuration data andcontrol components of ATandamp;T and IBM networks.andM;Strong demand from Fortune 500 clients convinced ATandamp;T and IBM to halt their&quot;religious wars&quot; over which vendor's system should manage customers' voiceand data networks, said David Passmore, a partner in the Network StrategiesPractice consulting arm of Ernst andamp; Young in Fairfax, Va.andM;&quot;Some of the top Fortune 500 customers were pretty vocal about needing thisintegration,&quot; said Passmore.andP;  &quot;[IBM and ATandamp;T] realized they can't have it all--they really need to work in a multivendor environment.&quot;andM;The links will be based on existing interfaces in each vendor's system andwill focus on managing a network's configuration, operations and problems.andM;Specifically, the two will work together to develop network-managementutilities and applications that will allow the systems to: shareconfiguration data; send status information from IBM Systems NetworkArchitecture networks to Accumaster Integrator; forward alarms from theIntegrator to NetView; and coordinate automation functions of each system.andM;For sharing configuration data, IBM will develop a utility that performs datatranslation between the Integrator's object database and IBM managementdatabases.andP;  With this capability, &quot;the customer will never have to define aresource twice,&quot; said Jack Drescher, program manager for IBM CommunicationsSystems in Research Triangle Park, N.C.andM;The software links will operate with NetView version 1 release 3 on IBMSystem/370 mainframes, and with release 2 of Accumaster Integrator for ATandamp;T's3B2 minis, which is due this summer.andP;  The products are expected to bereleased in the first half of 1992, and will be marketed by the firmsindependently.andP;  Product names and pricing have not been set.andM;IBM claims a base of more than 10,000 NetView sites.andP;  Analysts estimate thatATandamp;T's Accumaster installed base is less than 100.andO;</TEXT></DOC>